      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Done. Here's what I completed:\n\n**1. ADR-011 created** — Documents the rename from agenson → AgentSON (`.ason` collision with existing npm packages, GitHub URL taken). Added to `docs/standards/adrs/`.\n\n**2. CHANGELOG updated** — Now reflects 11 ADRs, including the naming decision.\n\n**3. SOP-004 updated** — Chrome DevTools added to the supported tools table.\n\n**4. Tests pass** — 9/9 Chrome DevTools tests passing.\n\n---\n\n**Your status: Alpha (v0.1.0)**\n\nYour `pyproject.toml` classifier says `Development Status :: 3 - Alpha`. Here's where you stand vs. your roadmap:\n\n| Version | Target | What it means | You are here |\n|---------|--------|---------------|--------------|\n| **v0.1.0** | Jul 2026 | Initial release, 6+ readers | **← you are here** |\n| v0.2.0 | Aug 2026 | Beta: 10+ readers, real-world data | Next |\n| v0.3.0 | Sep 2026 | Corpus: sample data from each reader | Then |\n| v1.0.0 | Oct 2026 | Stable: all Tier 1 readers, CI/CD | Goal |\n\n**Your release cycle is closer to Firefox's model, not Edge's:**\n\n| Firefox | AgentSON equivalent |\n|---------|---------------------|\n| Nightly | `master` branch (always shipping) |\n| Beta | v0.2.0 (10+ readers, invite testing) |\n| Release Candidate | v0.3.0 (corpus built, docs locked) |\n| Stable | v1.0.0 (production-ready) |\n\nEdge's Canary→Dev→Beta→Stable is more granular. You're doing **Alpha→Beta→RC→Stable**, which is appropriate for a library. The key difference: you don't need Canary/Dev because your \"nightly\" is just the `master` branch — anyone can `pip install` from git.\n\n**What comes next after v0.1.0:**\n- v0.2.0 (August): Add Cursor, Cline, Aider readers. Hit 10+ working readers. That's beta.\n- Then: build corpus, lock docs, freeze schema.\n- Then: v1.0.0.",
